<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="543" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1004]" box="[199,1375,692,717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,692,717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,423,693,716]" name="Japan" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">Japan</collectingCountry>
(Yakushima Is., Amami-Oshima Is., Okinawa Is., Ishigakijima Is., Iriomotejima Is.).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1004]" box="[199,721,727,752]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,330,727,752]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">Bionomics.</emphasis>
This is a forest-inhabiting species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="543" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1004]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,764,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is taken from Mr. Yuta Kudo, who supported us for material collecting in Yakushima Is.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="543" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1004]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,836,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is easily distinguished from the other Japanese species by having the asymmetric phallus and greatly reduced female abdominal 
<number box="[699,712,871,896]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543" value="7.0">7</number>
th sternite (
<figureCitation box="[848,925,871,896]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1883,1906]" captionTargetBox="[191,1389,219,1837]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[187,1389,195,1862]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Male 5 th sternite and terminalia of Cephalispa kudoi sp. nov.: 1. Male 5 th sternite in ventral view (setae omitted on the left side). 2. Same in lateral view (setae omitted). 3. Epandrium, surstylus and cerci in lateral view. 4. Same in dorsal view (setae omitted on the left side). 5. Hypandrium, postgonite and phallus in lateral view. 6. Distiphallus in dorsal view. (Abbreviations: cerc: cerci; epand: epandrium; hypand: hypandrium; pgt: postgonite; ph: phallus; sur: surstylus). (Scale bars = 0.2 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262975/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">Figs 6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[941,972,871,896]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 ‒ 27" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1498,1521]" captionTargetBox="[337,1248,196,1453]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[331,1256,193,1477]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 25 ‒ 27. Female terminalia of Cephalispa species in lateral view: 25. C. kudoi sp. nov. 26. C. okinawaensis sp. nov. 27. C. xanthogaster (Shinonaga, 2003) comb. nov. (Abbreviations: epi: epiproct; S 5: female 5 th sternite; S 6: female 6 th sternite; T 6: female 6 th tergite; T 7: female 7 th tergite; T 8: female 8 th tergite). (Scale bars = 0.2 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262980/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">25</figureCitation>
). This species is thought to be close to Chinese species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Cui &amp; Xue, 1995" authorityName="Cui &amp; Xue" authorityYear="1995" box="[344,672,908,933]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Cephalispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="543" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curtrata">
<emphasis box="[344,470,909,932]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">C. curtrata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Cui" box="[477,672,908,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543" refString="Cui, Y., Xue, W. &amp; Chen, C. (1995) A study of the genus Cephalispa Malloch of China (Diptera: Muscidae). Entomologia Sinica, 2, 18 - 34. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1744 - 7917.1995. tb 00019. x" type="journal article" year="1995">
Cui &amp; Xue, 
<number box="[616,672,908,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Cui &amp; Xue, 1995" authorityName="Cui &amp; Xue" authorityYear="1995" box="[727,1136,908,933]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Cephalispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="543" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviabdominis">
<emphasis box="[727,934,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">C. breviabdominis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Cui" box="[941,1136,908,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543" refString="Cui, Y., Xue, W. &amp; Chen, C. (1995) A study of the genus Cephalispa Malloch of China (Diptera: Muscidae). Entomologia Sinica, 2, 18 - 34. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1744 - 7917.1995. tb 00019. x" type="journal article" year="1995">
Cui &amp; Xue, 
<number box="[1080,1136,908,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by having the asymmetric phallus (
<bibRefCitation author="Cui" box="[247,428,943,968]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543" refString="Cui, Y., Xue, W. &amp; Chen, C. (1995) A study of the genus Cephalispa Malloch of China (Diptera: Muscidae). Entomologia Sinica, 2, 18 - 34. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1744 - 7917.1995. tb 00019. x" type="journal article" year="1995">
Cui 
<emphasis box="[297,347,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">et al</emphasis>
., 
<number box="[368,428,943,968]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). It is distinguishable from them by the narrowed surstylus at middle in dorsal view (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1883,1906]" captionTargetBox="[191,1389,219,1837]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[187,1389,195,1862]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Male 5 th sternite and terminalia of Cephalispa kudoi sp. nov.: 1. Male 5 th sternite in ventral view (setae omitted on the left side). 2. Same in lateral view (setae omitted). 3. Epandrium, surstylus and cerci in lateral view. 4. Same in dorsal view (setae omitted on the left side). 5. Hypandrium, postgonite and phallus in lateral view. 6. Distiphallus in dorsal view. (Abbreviations: cerc: cerci; epand: epandrium; hypand: hypandrium; pgt: postgonite; ph: phallus; sur: surstylus). (Scale bars = 0.2 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262975/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="543">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,168,980,1004]" pageId="3" pageNumber="543" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
